        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2017-09-06 22:47:16.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(4 comments)\n\n@Yunlong/Jinhua: Thanks for the reviews on the patch. But I have question regarding the MySQL/Redis installation. The reason I added them was because I see that Django expects a MySQL/Redis to be running since it is defined in the settings.py [1]. Also, the database interactions are done in the code base [2]. So, if we do not install a MySQL server, the API won’t run. I was thinking maybe you and Yunlong are looking at it from older VM perspective when all the component databases were in the same VM and hence the MySQL installation for GVNFM VNFMGR was not required. So, when I looked at the GVNFM VNFRES repo, I observed that the table required by GVNFM VNFMGR was found there [3]. So, to make the server to run, I had to add these MySQL installation scripts in GVNFM VNFMGR [4] as well. Without adding them, the database connections in the codebase don’t work and I can’t start the server. \n\nPlease look into this and let me know what you think about this. \n\n[1] – https://git.onap.org/vfc/gvnfm/vnfmgr/tree/mgr/mgr/settings.py - n80\n[2] – https://git.onap.org/vfc/gvnfm/vnfmgr/tree/mgr/mgr/vnfreg/views.py - n36\n[3] – https://git.onap.org/vfc/gvnfm/vnfres/tree/res/assembly/dbscripts/mysql/openo-gvnfm-vnfres-createobj.sql#n241\n[4] – https://gerrit.onap.org/r/ - /c/10413/2/mgr/docker/createobj.sql",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
